Java Execution Readiness – Pre-Development Locks (MVP)

Scope

This document locks the remaining execution-grade decisions needed to start Java backend development safely and avoid churn.

It builds on previously locked specs (Auth, Store, Orders, Payments, Payload Gateway, API conventions, Observability, Events).

⸻

1) Database Migrations & Schema Ownership (Locked)

1.1 Tooling
	•	Use Liquibase
	•	Use one shared schema for the platform database
	•	Use versioned SQL migrations (not XML/YAML)

1.2 Organization
	•	Migrations are grouped by module folders (logical ownership), e.g.:
	•	db/changelog/auth/
	•	db/changelog/store/
	•	db/changelog/orders/
	•	db/changelog/payments/
	•	db/changelog/content/

1.3 Rules
	•	Never edit already-applied migrations.
	•	Only append new migrations.
	•	Every migration must be reversible where reasonably possible (optional for MVP).

⸻

2) Multi-Tenancy Enforcement Guardrails (Locked)

2.1 TenantContext
	•	A TenantContext is derived from the tenant-scoped access token.
	•	TenantContext is available to service and repository layers.

2.2 Tenant scoping rule
	•	Every data-access query for tenant-owned entities MUST include tenant_id = <TenantContext.tenantId>.

2.3 Path vs token tenantId enforcement
	•	For Admin APIs: tenantId is in path and in token.
	•	Hard rule: pathTenantId == tokenTenantId enforced by centralized policy.

2.4 Testing requirement
	•	Add integration tests proving that cross-tenant reads/writes are blocked.

⸻

3) Concurrency & Idempotency (Locked)

3.1 Checkout idempotency
	•	Public POST /api/public/v1/checkout/orders supports optional Idempotency-Key.
	•	If provided, duplicate requests return the previously created order.

3.2 Order state transitions
	•	State transitions are enforced in a single DB transaction.
	•	Invalid transitions return 409 conflict.

3.3 Optimistic concurrency
	•	Use one of:
	•	a version column (optimistic locking), OR
	•	transactional “compare-and-set” state transition checks

MVP may start with state checks in transaction; versioning can be added later.

⸻

4) Media Handling (R2) Details (Locked)

4.1 Allowed formats and limits
	•	Supported formats: jpg, png, webp
	•	Max upload size: 10 MB per image

4.2 Processing
	•	MVP stores original images only.
	•	Resizing/thumbnails are deferred.

4.3 Object key naming
	•	R2 object keys are partitioned by tenant and entity:
	•	tenant/{tenantId}/products/{productId}/{mediaAssetId}

4.4 Access strategy
	•	Public read via CDN/public URL.
	•	Writes only via Java API.

⸻

5) Environments, Config, Secrets (Locked)

5.1 Environments
	•	Minimum environments: dev, prod (staging optional)

5.2 Secrets
	•	Secrets stored using environment secrets (Cloudflare secrets / platform secret store).
	•	Never store secrets in DB as plaintext.

5.3 Database connectivity
	•	Neon Postgres via HikariCP with conservative pooling.
	•	Timeouts and max connections tuned for low-cost MVP.

5.4 CORS
	•	Strict allowlist per environment.
	•	Public APIs allow only necessary origins.

⸻

6) Background Jobs Execution Model (Locked)

6.1 MVP execution
	•	Async side effects handled via in-process executor.

6.2 Reliability
	•	Webhook processing accepts request quickly and processes asynchronously.
	•	Failed processing uses retry with backoff.
	•	Dead-letter storage for repeated failures is recommended.

⸻

7) Minimal Test Strategy (Locked)

7.1 Required integration tests
	•	Tenant isolation
	•	Auth refresh rotation
	•	Payment webhook idempotency
	•	Order status transitions (confirm/fulfillment/cancel/refund)

7.2 Tooling
	•	Use Testcontainers for Postgres integration tests.
	•	Maintain a “golden path” suite that runs in CI.

⸻

Final Summary

All remaining pre-development execution decisions are now locked:
	•	Liquibase versioned SQL migrations with module folders
	•	TenantContext + strict tenant scoping guardrails
	•	Checkout idempotency + safe order state transitions
	•	R2 media constraints and naming conventions
	•	Minimal environment/secrets/db configuration principles
	•	In-process jobs + retry/dead-letter posture
	•	Integration test minimum set with Testcontainers

This document is locked and development-ready.